{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623149"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:08:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16837"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.04,0.06,0.71,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70402"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55866"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5044"},{"type":"tags","id":"5046"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22900"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70402"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers are commonly used to treat cardiac arrhythmias and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Block T-type calcium channels in cardiac tissue","Block sodium channels in cardiac tissue","Block potassium channels in vascular smooth muscle","Block L-type calcium channels in cardiac tissue","Block beta-adrenergic receptors in cardiac tissue"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking L-type calcium channels in cardiac tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. This action reduces calcium influx into cardiac myocytes and nodal cells, leading to:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecreased conduction through the AV node.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReduced contractility (negative inotropy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecreased heart rate (negative chronotropy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking T-type calcium channels in cardiac tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While these drugs may have some effect on T-type channels, their primary therapeutic action occurs through L-type calcium channel blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking sodium channels in cardiac tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism belongs to class I antiarrhythmic medications such as flecainide, which have different therapeutic applications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking potassium channels in vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - Although calcium channel blockers affect vascular smooth muscle, they act by blocking calcium channels rather than potassium channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking beta-adrenergic receptors in cardiac tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the mechanism of beta blockers, which are a different class of cardiovascular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe two main non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers are verapamil and diltiazem. Their cardiac effects make them particularly useful for treating supraventricular tachycardia and rate control in atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers (verapamil, diltiazem) reduce cardiac conduction and contractility by blocking L-type calcium channels.","Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers have greater effects on cardiac tissue than vascular smooth muscle.","These drugs are useful in treating supraventricular tachycardia and atrial fibrillation due to their effects on AV node conduction."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55866"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55866"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T21:46:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T21:47:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70402"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag